"&#xa0;\nMotoring Organisations’ Land Access and Recreation Association (LARA) – Written evidenceSummary of Key Issues•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWe support the work and consensus recommendations of the Stakeholder Working Group, which underpin this part of the Bill. Our members are not\n&#xa0;\ndirectly\n&#xa0;\naffected by the proposals in sections 12-18 of the Bill and the associated Schedules, and we su\np\nport the\n&#xa0;\nStakeholder Working Group’s recommendations (only) as contained within the Bill.\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWe are very concerned that groups such as the Green Lanes Environmental Action Movement (GLEAM) and the Peak District Green Lanes Association (PDGLA), each with a single-issue objective to restrict or destroy our members’ lawful activities, are making representations such that additional traffic regulation provisions are introduced by the Deregulation Bill, and/or that all unsealed public roads and byways open to all traffic are administratively downgraded to restricted byway status.\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThese issues have not been before the Stakeholder Working Group, have not been through any process of public consultation, and are not objectively evidence-based. Far from being deregulatory, these proposals will operate to increase local authority and p\no\nlice burdens.\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLARA believes that there is no evidential case made for any of these proposals, that they will introduce an additional layer of regulation and burden, and that any change in this area of law and practice should first go through a proper process of public consu\nl\ntation.\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAny countryside access \norganisation\n (including GLEAM and PDGLA) is able to bring such proposals directly to the Countryside Minister, and to the Rights of Way Review Committee, which is constituted and operated to receive and consider such matters and to make recommendations to the Government.\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn our respectful view, what is being proposed to the Committee is not deregulatory, and is simply an attempt to use the Deregulation Bill 2013 to circumvent a proper pr\no\ncess of public consultation by the appropriate Government Department, and (if nece\ns\nsary) a full and proper process in Parliament.\n&#xa0;\nOur EvidenceWhat is LARA?Financial benefits to the rural communityDisinformation about our activities&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRecreational motoring on unsealed roads and byways is an emotive and complex issue. Some people think that motor vehicles should simply be banned from unsealed roads and nothing is easily going to change that view, but there is increasingly a ‘middle ground’ approach from highway authorities, which seeks to apply a considered ‘least r\ne\nstrictive approach’ philosophy to traffic management on our minor highways.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLARA believes that consensus management of motor traffic on unsealed roads, appr\no\npriate to the circumstances in each case, together with sufficient maintenance and a r\ne\nalistic expectation of what a byway should be like, is the way ahead.\nThe situation since 2006The standard and cost of maintenance and repairGreen roads&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThere was no evidence of widespread damage to the byway network from motor vehicles.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n42% of use was land management, 38% of use was recreational, and 20% of use was a\nc\ncess to property, with recreational use at 38%. If all unsealed roads were downgraded to restricted byways, the land management and access uses would remain with no benefit ot\nh\ner than a discriminatory penalty to recreational users.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMotor vehicles can have a beneficial effect, in that they prevent byways becoming ove\nr\ngrown.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nByways are an important resource for people with disabilities ... the ability to drive motor vehicles on byways.\nStone roadsWhat is a classic reliability trial?Classic trials and the rural communityClassic trials and the effect of NERCA 2006&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\n&#xa0;\n"